<subSubSection lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="304" pageId="2" pageNumber="303" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,1925,2022]" lastBlockId="3.[151,1437,151,824]" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="304" pageId="2" pageNumber="303">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,344,1925,1950]" pageId="2" pageNumber="303">Description.</emphasis>
As in 
<bibRefCitation author="Platnick" box="[419,713,1925,1950]" pageId="2" pageNumber="303" refString="Platnick, N. I. &amp; Shadab, M. U. (1984) A revision of the neotropical spiders of the genus Apopyllus (Araneae, Gnaphosidae). American Museum Novitates, 2788, 1 - 9." type="journal article" year="1984">Platnick &amp; Shadab (1984)</bibRefCitation>
, except for the male and female genitalia, which are redescribed below, and for the presence of terminal pseudosegmentation of tarsi IV in both sexes (
<figureCitation box="[1108,1175,1961,1986]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1154,1176]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,223,1131]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,223,1132]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 2. Apopyllus silvestrii (female and legs: UFMG 8323; male: CASENT 9051658): A Epigynum, ventral view. B Vulva, dorsal view. C Expanded male right palp, retrolateral view. D Tarsus of leg IV, showing pseudosegmentation and claw (insert). Abbreviations: AR: anterior ridge, AK: apical keel of retrolateral tibial apophysis, CI: cymbial incision, DK: dorsal keel of retrolateral tibial apophysis, EB: embolus base, ET: embolus tip, LF: lateral field, MA: median apophysis, MF: median field, MTE: membranous tegular extension, PP: paramedian pockets, SS: secondary spermathecae, ST: subtegulum, T: tegulum, Tu: tubercle of retrolateral tibial apophysis, VK: Ventral keel of retrolateral tibial apophysis." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/261075/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="303">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
D). The female internal genitalia (vulva) of 
<taxonomicName box="[377,489,1997,2021]" class="Arachnida" family="Gnaphosidae" genus="Apopyllus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="303" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[377,489,1997,2021]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="303">Apopyllus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are composed of a pair of highly convoluted copulatory ducts, a pair of secondary spermathecae (blind end receptacles with large glandular pores), a pair of primary spermathecae that are connected to a pair of fertilization ducts (
<figureCitation box="[537,612,188,213]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1649,1671]" captionTargetBox="[151,1430,337,1615]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,337,1628]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Genital Morphology of Apopyllus. A, B A. malleco female; C, D A silvestrii male. A Vulva, dorsal view. B Epigynum, ventral view. Vulva can be seen by transparency. C Male palp, ventral view. D Male palp, retrolateral view. Abbreviations: ACT: anterior curled tracts, AR: anterior ridge, CI: cymbial incision, CP: cymbial projection, Cy: cymbium, E: embolus, FD: fertilization duct, LAT: lateral ascendant tract, LDT: lateral descendant tract, LL: lateral loop, MA: median apophysis, MTE: membranous tegular extension, PAT: paramedian ascendant tract, PDT: paramedian descendant tract, PP: paramedian pockets, PPD: proximal part of copulatory duct, PS: primary spermathecae, RTA: retrolateral tibial apophysis, SS: secondary spermathecae, ST: subtegulum, T: tegulum, TPD: terminal part of copulatory duct. (Many of the abbreviations are not present in this plate, but present in other plates, as Fig. 2)" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/261074/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="304">Figs 1</figureCitation>
A–B, 2B). The copulatory ducts, though variable between and within species, have a basic structure shared by all species (
<figureCitation box="[761,830,223,248]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1649,1671]" captionTargetBox="[151,1430,337,1615]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,337,1628]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Genital Morphology of Apopyllus. A, B A. malleco female; C, D A silvestrii male. A Vulva, dorsal view. B Epigynum, ventral view. Vulva can be seen by transparency. C Male palp, ventral view. D Male palp, retrolateral view. Abbreviations: ACT: anterior curled tracts, AR: anterior ridge, CI: cymbial incision, CP: cymbial projection, Cy: cymbium, E: embolus, FD: fertilization duct, LAT: lateral ascendant tract, LDT: lateral descendant tract, LL: lateral loop, MA: median apophysis, MTE: membranous tegular extension, PAT: paramedian ascendant tract, PDT: paramedian descendant tract, PP: paramedian pockets, PPD: proximal part of copulatory duct, PS: primary spermathecae, RTA: retrolateral tibial apophysis, SS: secondary spermathecae, ST: subtegulum, T: tegulum, TPD: terminal part of copulatory duct. (Many of the abbreviations are not present in this plate, but present in other plates, as Fig. 2)" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/261074/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="304">Figs 1</figureCitation>
A–B). The copulatory opening leads to the proximal part of the copulatory duct (PPD) that is ventrally located and has a “U” shape. It curves dorsally and goes towards the posterior part of epigynum, forming the paramedian descendant tract (PDT). The PDT curves towards the anterior part, forming the lateral ascendant tract (
<collectionCode box="[700,758,332,356]" country="USA" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:13973" name="Saint Vincent College" pageId="3" pageNumber="304">LAT</collectionCode>
). It extends anteriorly to the copulatory opening forming the anterior curled tract (ACT). The ACT leads to a ventral tract that goes posteriorly, called lateral descendent tract (LDT). It curves forming the lateral loop (LL) and then the paramedian ascendant tract (
<collectionCode box="[1182,1236,404,428]" country="France" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:15201" name="Mus�um National d'Histoire Naturelle" pageId="3" pageNumber="304">PAT</collectionCode>
). The 
<collectionCode box="[1307,1354,404,428]" country="France" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:15201" name="Mus�um National d'Histoire Naturelle" pageId="3" pageNumber="304">PAT</collectionCode>
curves dorsally leading to the terminal part of the copulatory duct (TPD), which ends at the primary spermatheca. The secondary spermatheca is a rounded blind sac of variable size that arises from the lateral loop.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,151,824]" pageId="3" pageNumber="304">
Male genitalia have a small subtegulum that can be seen in ventral view on unexpanded palp (
<figureCitation box="[1281,1346,511,536]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1649,1671]" captionTargetBox="[151,1430,337,1615]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,337,1628]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Genital Morphology of Apopyllus. A, B A. malleco female; C, D A silvestrii male. A Vulva, dorsal view. B Epigynum, ventral view. Vulva can be seen by transparency. C Male palp, ventral view. D Male palp, retrolateral view. Abbreviations: ACT: anterior curled tracts, AR: anterior ridge, CI: cymbial incision, CP: cymbial projection, Cy: cymbium, E: embolus, FD: fertilization duct, LAT: lateral ascendant tract, LDT: lateral descendant tract, LL: lateral loop, MA: median apophysis, MTE: membranous tegular extension, PAT: paramedian ascendant tract, PDT: paramedian descendant tract, PP: paramedian pockets, PPD: proximal part of copulatory duct, PS: primary spermathecae, RTA: retrolateral tibial apophysis, SS: secondary spermathecae, ST: subtegulum, T: tegulum, TPD: terminal part of copulatory duct. (Many of the abbreviations are not present in this plate, but present in other plates, as Fig. 2)" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/261074/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="304">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
C). The tegulum is rounded to oval, with an elongated, partially sclerotized, hook shaped median apophysis (
<figureCitation box="[1283,1351,548,573]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1649,1671]" captionTargetBox="[151,1430,337,1615]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,337,1628]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Genital Morphology of Apopyllus. A, B A. malleco female; C, D A silvestrii male. A Vulva, dorsal view. B Epigynum, ventral view. Vulva can be seen by transparency. C Male palp, ventral view. D Male palp, retrolateral view. Abbreviations: ACT: anterior curled tracts, AR: anterior ridge, CI: cymbial incision, CP: cymbial projection, Cy: cymbium, E: embolus, FD: fertilization duct, LAT: lateral ascendant tract, LDT: lateral descendant tract, LL: lateral loop, MA: median apophysis, MTE: membranous tegular extension, PAT: paramedian ascendant tract, PDT: paramedian descendant tract, PP: paramedian pockets, PPD: proximal part of copulatory duct, PS: primary spermathecae, RTA: retrolateral tibial apophysis, SS: secondary spermathecae, ST: subtegulum, T: tegulum, TPD: terminal part of copulatory duct. (Many of the abbreviations are not present in this plate, but present in other plates, as Fig. 2)" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/261074/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="304">Figs 1</figureCitation>
C, 2C), and with a long bifid membranous tegular extension (MTE) that supports a long coiled embolus (
<figureCitation box="[1248,1315,583,608]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1649,1671]" captionTargetBox="[151,1430,337,1615]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,337,1628]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Genital Morphology of Apopyllus. A, B A. malleco female; C, D A silvestrii male. A Vulva, dorsal view. B Epigynum, ventral view. Vulva can be seen by transparency. C Male palp, ventral view. D Male palp, retrolateral view. Abbreviations: ACT: anterior curled tracts, AR: anterior ridge, CI: cymbial incision, CP: cymbial projection, Cy: cymbium, E: embolus, FD: fertilization duct, LAT: lateral ascendant tract, LDT: lateral descendant tract, LL: lateral loop, MA: median apophysis, MTE: membranous tegular extension, PAT: paramedian ascendant tract, PDT: paramedian descendant tract, PP: paramedian pockets, PPD: proximal part of copulatory duct, PS: primary spermathecae, RTA: retrolateral tibial apophysis, SS: secondary spermathecae, ST: subtegulum, T: tegulum, TPD: terminal part of copulatory duct. (Many of the abbreviations are not present in this plate, but present in other plates, as Fig. 2)" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/261074/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="304">Figs 1</figureCitation>
C–D, 2C). The embolus articulates with the tegulum by a long distal tubular membrane (DTM) (
<figureCitation box="[1118,1185,620,645]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1154,1176]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,223,1131]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,223,1132]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 2. Apopyllus silvestrii (female and legs: UFMG 8323; male: CASENT 9051658): A Epigynum, ventral view. B Vulva, dorsal view. C Expanded male right palp, retrolateral view. D Tarsus of leg IV, showing pseudosegmentation and claw (insert). Abbreviations: AR: anterior ridge, AK: apical keel of retrolateral tibial apophysis, CI: cymbial incision, DK: dorsal keel of retrolateral tibial apophysis, EB: embolus base, ET: embolus tip, LF: lateral field, MA: median apophysis, MF: median field, MTE: membranous tegular extension, PP: paramedian pockets, SS: secondary spermathecae, ST: subtegulum, T: tegulum, Tu: tubercle of retrolateral tibial apophysis, VK: Ventral keel of retrolateral tibial apophysis." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/261075/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="304">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
C). The RTA is folded in an elaborated structure, with ventral, dorsal and apical serrated keels (
<figureCitation box="[972,1041,655,680]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1154,1176]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,223,1131]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,223,1132]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 2. Apopyllus silvestrii (female and legs: UFMG 8323; male: CASENT 9051658): A Epigynum, ventral view. B Vulva, dorsal view. C Expanded male right palp, retrolateral view. D Tarsus of leg IV, showing pseudosegmentation and claw (insert). Abbreviations: AR: anterior ridge, AK: apical keel of retrolateral tibial apophysis, CI: cymbial incision, DK: dorsal keel of retrolateral tibial apophysis, EB: embolus base, ET: embolus tip, LF: lateral field, MA: median apophysis, MF: median field, MTE: membranous tegular extension, PP: paramedian pockets, SS: secondary spermathecae, ST: subtegulum, T: tegulum, Tu: tubercle of retrolateral tibial apophysis, VK: Ventral keel of retrolateral tibial apophysis." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/261075/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="304">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
C). The cymbium has a retrolateral projection ventrally incised (CP, in 
<figureCitation box="[548,613,692,717]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1649,1671]" captionTargetBox="[151,1430,337,1615]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,337,1628]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Genital Morphology of Apopyllus. A, B A. malleco female; C, D A silvestrii male. A Vulva, dorsal view. B Epigynum, ventral view. Vulva can be seen by transparency. C Male palp, ventral view. D Male palp, retrolateral view. Abbreviations: ACT: anterior curled tracts, AR: anterior ridge, CI: cymbial incision, CP: cymbial projection, Cy: cymbium, E: embolus, FD: fertilization duct, LAT: lateral ascendant tract, LDT: lateral descendant tract, LL: lateral loop, MA: median apophysis, MTE: membranous tegular extension, PAT: paramedian ascendant tract, PDT: paramedian descendant tract, PP: paramedian pockets, PPD: proximal part of copulatory duct, PS: primary spermathecae, RTA: retrolateral tibial apophysis, SS: secondary spermathecae, ST: subtegulum, T: tegulum, TPD: terminal part of copulatory duct. (Many of the abbreviations are not present in this plate, but present in other plates, as Fig. 2)" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/261074/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="304">Figs 1</figureCitation>
C–D, 2C).
</paragraph>
